aVMany animals gather in large groups
p6
aVthat are among the most wonderful spectacles
p7
aVin the natural world.
p8
aVBut why do these groups form?
p9
aVThe common answers include things like
p10
aVseeking safety in numbers or hunting in packs
p11
aVor gathering to mate or breed,
p12
aVand all of these explanations,
p13
aVwhile often true,
p14
aVmake a huge assumption about animal behavior,
p15
aVthat the animals are in control of their own actions,
p16
aVthat they are in charge of their bodies.
p17
aVAnd that is often not the case.
p18
aa(lp19
VThis is Artemia, a brine shrimp.
p20
aVYou probably know it better as a sea monkey.
p21
aVIt's small, and it typically lives alone,
p22
aVbut it can gather in these large red swarms
p23
aVthat span for meters,
p24
aVand these form because of a parasite.
p25
aVThese shrimp are infected with a tapeworm.
p26
aVA tapeworm is effectively a long, living gut
p27
aVwith genitals at one end and a hooked mouth at the other.
p28
aVAs a freelance journalist, I sympathize.
p29
aV(Laughter)
p30
aVThe tapeworm drains nutrients from Artemia's body,
p31
aVbut it also does other things.
p32
aVIt castrates them,
p33
aVit changes their color from transparent to bright red,
p34
aVit makes them live longer,
p35
aVand as biologist Nicolas Rode has found,
p36
aVit makes them swim in groups.
p37
aVWhy? Because the tapeworm, like many other parasites,
p38
aVhas a complicated life cycle
p39
aVinvolving many different hosts.
p40
aVThe shrimp are just one step on its journey.
p41
aVIts ultimate destination is this,
p42
aVthe greater flamingo.
p43
aVOnly in a flamingo can the tapeworm reproduce,
p44
aVso to get there, it manipulates its shrimp hosts
p45
aVinto forming these conspicuous colored swarms
p46
aVthat are easier for a flamingo to spot
p47
aVand to devour,
p48
aVand that is the secret of the Artemia swarm.
p49
aVThey aren't sociable through their own volition,
p50
aVbut because they are being controlled.
p51
aVIt's not safety in numbers.
p52
aVIt's actually the exact opposite.
p53
aVThe tapeworm hijacks their brains and their bodies,
p54
aVturning them into vehicles
p55
aVfor getting itself into a flamingo.
